edu.umd.cs.datastructures.projectskeletons.tavl

Class ThreadedAVLTree<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.umd.cs.datastructures.projectskeletons.tavl.ThreadedAVLTree<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The Comparable type held by the data structure.

    public class ThreadedAVLTree<T extends java.lang.Comparable<T>>
extends java.lang.Object

    ThreadedAVLTree implements threaded Adelson-Velsky-Landis (AVL) trees (TAVL trees). These trees:

    1. Allow for efficient lookup, insertion and deletion in O(logn) time, by virtue of being AVL trees.
    2. Perform a full inorder traversal in O(n) time, by virtue of being threaded trees.

    Hence, two powerful ideas that we have talked about in lecture will now be combined in one data structure.

      • height

        public int height()
        Return the height of the tree. The height of the tree is defined as the length of the longest path between the root and the leaf level. By definition of path length, a stub tree has a height of 0, and we define an empty tree to have a height of -1.
        Returns:
        The height of the tree.

      • inorderTraversal

        public java.util.Iterator<T> inorderTraversal()
        Generate an inorder traversal over the tree's stored keys. This should be done by using the tree's threads, to be able to find every inorder successor in amortized constant time. TO GET CREDIT IN RELATED UNIT TESTS, YOU MUST USE THE TREE'S THREADS TO GENERATE THE TRAVERSAL! IN FACT, YOU SHOULD NOT HAVE ANY KIND OF RECURSION IN THE IMPLEMENTATION OF THIS METHOD, NOR SHOULD YOU USE A STACK OF ANY KIND! WE WILL CHECK YOUR SOURCE CODE TO MAKE SURE YOU ADHERE TO THESE SPECIFICATIONS FOR THE RELEVANT TEST CREDIT!
        Returns:
        An Iterator over Ts, which exposes the elements in ascending order. If the tree is empty, the Iterator's first call to Iterator.hasNext() will return false.
